1
00:00:15,050 --> 00:00:19,470
Right.

2
00:00:19,470 --> 00:00:22,970
Hello, yep, good, thank you.

3
00:00:22,970 --> 00:00:29,170
Well, greetings all, and it's wonderful to see all of you here.

4
00:00:29,190 --> 00:00:33,430
And this is our last Basil's Table.

5
00:00:33,430 --> 00:00:38,010
Now, I want to point out, this sounds rather self-centered when I say Basil's Table.

6
00:00:38,010 --> 00:00:39,370
The title was not mine.

7
00:00:39,370 --> 00:00:43,050
It was actually done by Triple 8, and they thought it would be a good idea to have Basil's Table.

8
00:00:43,570 --> 00:00:47,310
So, this is an extension of a number of series that we have had.

9
00:00:47,330 --> 00:00:49,690
And I'd like to welcome you all.

10
00:00:49,690 --> 00:01:07,770
But before we start the welcome, I think it's important that we acknowledge that the First Nations people, as the traditional owners of the land, which we are here for this discussion taking place, the Wurundjeri people of the Kulin Nation, and I pay respects to all elders, past, present and emerging.

11
00:01:09,690 --> 00:01:13,110
My job is going to be actually very, very wonderful.

12
00:01:13,110 --> 00:01:27,250
All I have to do is to actually introduce the speakers, who are, as you can see, the array there, and they are all very interesting people, and they've done some very interesting work.

13
00:01:27,270 --> 00:01:34,690
And the first one is Elena, whom I've met before, who is an architect and is doing a Ph.D.

14
00:01:34,690 --> 00:01:50,730
at Deakin University, and she specializes in substantial, or sustainable, sorry, urban systems, regenerative development, participative planning, co-design, and collaborative housing.

15
00:01:50,730 --> 00:01:52,870
Now, that's amazing, isn't it?

16
00:01:52,870 --> 00:02:13,290
To think that an architect is going to do all that, or lead that, with experience across public buildings, including international aquariums, local education projects, apartments, and private residential, the focus has moved from environmental and socially sustainable design.

17
00:02:14,990 --> 00:02:28,210
Jose, who is the writer of the end, whom I also had the pleasure of meeting, who is also a very interesting man, who is sort of from the States originally, and now in Australia.

18
00:02:28,210 --> 00:02:38,570
He holds a doctorate from the Queensland University of Technology in critical globalization studies, winning their award for the outstanding doctoral thesis.

19
00:02:38,570 --> 00:02:41,730
So we are honored to have you, Jose.

20
00:02:41,750 --> 00:02:57,450
And amazingly that he sort of has published over 70 articles, chapters and papers and focuses his research on the experience and prefigurative innovations we need to navigate the epic times we live in.

21
00:02:58,850 --> 00:03:12,130
And talking about the epic times we live in, that is really, we would like you to think about and ponder about that because we are living what an old Chinese curse is to be in very interesting times.

22
00:03:12,130 --> 00:03:17,270
Because for the first time, I think, we have to be, we have used that.

23
00:03:17,270 --> 00:03:18,470
I think, where is Jacques?

24
00:03:20,670 --> 00:03:21,490
There is Jacques?

25
00:03:21,490 --> 00:03:22,670
Jacques, yes.

26
00:03:22,670 --> 00:03:33,170
But Jacques and I go back decades, where we used to talk about the importance of justice in terms of thinking locally and thinking globally.

27
00:03:33,170 --> 00:03:40,170
And now we actually know, because of the world that we are in, we have to be thinking locally.

28
00:03:40,170 --> 00:03:47,170
First, I used to say globally before, but now I think it's thinking locally and think what are the ramifications of that globally.

29
00:03:49,190 --> 00:03:55,310
Then, the next person is Bridgette, who is a professional futurist.

30
00:03:55,310 --> 00:03:56,830
My word, futurist.

31
00:03:56,850 --> 00:03:59,310
That's awesome, awesome.

32
00:04:00,890 --> 00:04:02,170
Because who can tell on the future?

33
00:04:02,170 --> 00:04:13,910
But anyway, she's a professional futurist and para-academic who is curious about post-growth innovation and design in crisis.

34
00:04:13,910 --> 00:04:20,310
She teaches strategic foresight, innovation and entrepreneurship at Swinburne.

35
00:04:20,310 --> 00:04:35,090
Bridgette asks a lot of questions and doesn't play golf, which I think is a tragedy, and enjoys more than the odd glass of wine, I'm glad.

36
00:04:37,270 --> 00:04:40,590
So, welcome.

37
00:04:40,590 --> 00:04:45,390
And then we have Alexa Pantitichan.

38
00:04:45,390 --> 00:04:55,010
He's a technologist and social entrepreneur with a focus on distributed technologies and large scale cooperation.

39
00:04:55,010 --> 00:05:07,690
Trained as an engineer, Alexa has the vision of technologically advanced Australia with active regional hubs and is currently the acting president of Linux.

40
00:05:07,690 --> 00:05:09,550
Is that how you pronounce it?

41
00:05:09,550 --> 00:05:09,950
Yeah.

42
00:05:12,110 --> 00:05:21,130
Linux, users of Victoria, it's interesting, and an organizer designing open democracy and blockchain for social impact.

43
00:05:22,450 --> 00:05:30,070
And I'm supposed to introduce myself according to Antony, our wonderful chair.

44
00:05:30,070 --> 00:05:31,930
Well, my name is Basil Varghese.

45
00:05:31,930 --> 00:05:43,110
I am sometimes, I suppose, one of these ancient people who have been involved with social justice issues for over 50 years.

46
00:05:43,110 --> 00:05:52,550
I think the time that drew my passion was really to do with the Vietnam War, black rights, the anti-apartheid movement.

47
00:05:54,050 --> 00:05:59,850
And I've been involved with those issues, at least when it comes to racism and gender.

48
00:05:59,850 --> 00:06:02,950
And now I'm involved with 888 as their patron.

49
00:06:02,950 --> 00:06:10,310
And also I'm involved with The Voice, which I think is a crucial thing for Australia to face.

50
00:06:10,310 --> 00:06:16,630
And I don't think I'll, I don't like talking about myself, but anyway, I've gone, done work with lots of, lots of people.

51
00:06:16,830 --> 00:06:22,290
Also with, there's here Jeannie from the Brotherhood of St. Lawrence, where I spent a lot of time there.

52
00:06:22,290 --> 00:06:25,710
And so it's been, for me, it's been a wonderful time.

53
00:06:25,710 --> 00:06:32,250
And now my role is to affirm and support young talent.

54
00:06:32,250 --> 00:06:34,850
I believe we need to support and affirm them.

55
00:06:34,850 --> 00:06:40,010
So, and I hope you get all the affirmation to do your work.

56
00:06:41,910 --> 00:06:52,630
And now I'd like to introduce our chair, Antony, who has put a lot of work into this with Sonja, where is she?

57
00:06:52,630 --> 00:06:53,710
There.

58
00:06:53,710 --> 00:06:54,650
And again, thank you.

59
00:07:05,550 --> 00:07:08,390
Yeah, yeah, yeah, thank you.

60
00:07:08,390 --> 00:07:10,970
Well, look, welcome, everybody.

61
00:07:11,350 --> 00:07:12,910
It's December, isn't it?

62
00:07:14,650 --> 00:07:19,690
And sometimes events are a bit, you know, up and down, you're not quite sure how many people come along.

63
00:07:19,690 --> 00:07:23,210
It's crazy, we have people saying, oh yeah, I'm coming.

64
00:07:24,530 --> 00:07:27,130
Oh, yeah, but I'm coming, yeah, we'll book.

65
00:07:27,130 --> 00:07:29,610
And then someone says, oh no, I'm not coming, but I'm coming.

66
00:07:29,610 --> 00:07:39,290
And then all of these last minutes, and they just go, we were going to have a long table, and then we weren't, but then a long table stayed.

67
00:07:39,290 --> 00:07:46,070
So it's just December, things go really strangely, but it's lovely to see you all here.

68
00:07:46,070 --> 00:07:51,190
My name is Antony McMullen, I'm the chair of the 888 Co-operative Causeway.

69
00:07:51,190 --> 00:07:52,810
So we're a cooperative.

70
00:07:53,290 --> 00:07:55,070
I just have your assistance there.

71
00:07:55,610 --> 00:07:57,750
Oh, okay.

72
00:07:57,750 --> 00:07:58,590
Yeah, no worries.

73
00:07:58,590 --> 00:07:59,390
How's that?

74
00:07:59,390 --> 00:08:01,730
Is that really loud, isn't it?

75
00:08:01,730 --> 00:08:02,790
Yeah, yeah.

76
00:08:02,790 --> 00:08:05,130
I'm sure you can hear me.

77
00:08:05,950 --> 00:08:07,990
Yeah, cool, cool.

78
00:08:07,990 --> 00:08:12,570
Yeah, so we're a little cooperative co-working space in the middle of the city.

79
00:08:12,570 --> 00:08:20,830
Basil, who's our patron, is also our landlord and has been very supportive of our cooperative and running these events.

80
00:08:21,530 --> 00:08:42,250
So we not only provide co-working space for our members, we also want to contribute to discussions about the social economy and thinking about new ways of being, new ways of doing business, new ways of being in the world.

81
00:08:42,270 --> 00:09:01,550
And we thought we'd end the year on something a little bit more kind of speculative, a little bit more big picture, because we've had some quite sort of practical discussions and things like that, but we thought, yeah, we would like to sort of think about the future a little bit.

82
00:09:01,550 --> 00:09:04,530
And we're in a really difficult time.

83
00:09:04,770 --> 00:09:12,370
We're looking at parts of Australia that will be already uninsurable because of climate change.

84
00:09:13,530 --> 00:09:20,030
We have got a lot of the institutions that we've trusted over many years are starting to break down.

85
00:09:20,030 --> 00:09:24,450
We're concerned about corruption at different levels.

86
00:09:24,450 --> 00:09:27,110
There's a polarisation between people.

87
00:09:27,110 --> 00:09:34,570
So what people could agree to disagree on previously, now they can really come at loggerheads.

88
00:09:34,570 --> 00:09:45,230
So cooperation, is it something that is going to become, it's going to become something that is more important for us in communities?

89
00:09:45,230 --> 00:09:47,230
So how can we work together?

90
00:09:47,430 --> 00:09:49,270
If we can't get insurance, are we going to stay here?

91
00:09:49,270 --> 00:09:51,450
What are we going to do?

92
00:09:51,450 --> 00:10:00,050
How are we going to build local institutions in a way that sustains us in very difficult economic times?

93
00:10:00,050 --> 00:10:03,830
So we've got the sort of global dislocation there.

94
00:10:03,830 --> 00:10:15,830
So we are, as Basil mentioned, living in quite interesting times, as they say, but we have a very interesting panel, which have all been introduced and welcomed.

95
00:10:16,010 --> 00:10:21,070
And it's such a pleasure to have you all here as part of this discussion.

96
00:10:21,070 --> 00:10:28,090
And I thought we would start the discussion with really what drives you.

97
00:10:28,090 --> 00:10:35,250
So you've come, you've given your time this evening to talk about the future, to talk about technology.

98
00:10:35,250 --> 00:10:38,290
We're going to have a discussion about those really important things.

99
00:10:38,290 --> 00:10:45,010
But before we do that, I'm interested in what drives you, why you do what you do.

100
00:10:45,030 --> 00:10:51,690
And yeah, just talk a little bit maybe about where you come from, bit of your story and where you'd like to go.

101
00:10:51,690 --> 00:10:55,270
So there's no particular order here.

102
00:10:55,270 --> 00:10:58,750
And Alexei, you are holding the microphone.

103
00:10:58,750 --> 00:11:02,290
So you can go first if you like.

104
00:11:07,950 --> 00:11:09,150
Thank you.

105
00:11:09,150 --> 00:11:13,890
Was worried you were going to pass it on to me, but then the word came to me.

106
00:11:13,890 --> 00:11:18,750
The drive for me is, I think, I can say it in one word, is potential.

107
00:11:18,750 --> 00:11:21,130
I was trained as an electrical engineer.

108
00:11:21,130 --> 00:11:29,550
And electrical grids are the largest one-piece system that the mankind has made.

109
00:11:29,550 --> 00:11:32,930
It's a very interesting piece because it can just fail and you have to black out.

110
00:11:32,930 --> 00:11:41,150
So when you deal with electrical engineering systems and software, you realize how big systems are like and really influence my thinking.

111
00:11:41,150 --> 00:11:50,870
And you grow up and you build up an understanding of policies and how society works and economic and everything.

112
00:11:50,870 --> 00:11:58,730
And I saw the very same principles that we were learning in electrical engineering and engineering as a whole.

113
00:11:59,610 --> 00:12:02,730
I can use the same to understand social systems.

114
00:12:02,730 --> 00:12:10,590
And then I could see the huge potential that we can have as humans when the information flows differently.

115
00:12:11,730 --> 00:12:22,490
It's a bit hard to explain, but as again, it was being reflected in the things that I was doing as I switched to IT.

116
00:12:22,490 --> 00:12:24,610
And in IT, we have a lot of very interesting things.

117
00:12:24,890 --> 00:12:30,770
One of them is hackathons, is events where people come together.

118
00:12:30,770 --> 00:12:33,330
Normally, over a weekend, they form teams.

119
00:12:33,330 --> 00:12:37,470
Sometimes they don't even know each other before they come to the venue.

120
00:12:37,470 --> 00:12:39,310
They form teams two hours later.

121
00:12:39,310 --> 00:12:46,290
They're starting ideating and one and a half day later, they're in front of judges and presenting the work that they've done together.

122
00:12:46,290 --> 00:12:55,290
And it's amazing to see when things are facilitated and trust is established between people through some mechanisms.

123
00:12:55,290 --> 00:12:57,290
How much people can achieve together.

124
00:12:57,290 --> 00:12:58,910
It almost looks like magic.

125
00:12:58,910 --> 00:13:00,950
And I've seen a lot of these cases.

126
00:13:02,690 --> 00:13:14,490
And I was lucky to be a contractor in having short contracts in different types of organizations and universities and governments and smaller startups.

127
00:13:14,490 --> 00:13:25,390
And I saw where people are organized, workforce are organized in a way that they can't really express themselves and all sorts of things.

128
00:13:25,390 --> 00:13:28,250
How the whole organization is very slow and has a lot of problems.

129
00:13:28,250 --> 00:13:39,470
But when the information flows between people and there's dignity and respect, how small teams can carry really heavy weights and countless examples of that in tech that I can name.

130
00:13:39,550 --> 00:13:50,330
So that's what drives me, like the potential that we can achieve if we can basically work out to how to work together.

131
00:13:50,330 --> 00:13:54,730
And there needs to be no compromise as far as I've come to believe.

132
00:13:57,050 --> 00:13:58,170
Thank you, Alexa.

133
00:13:58,170 --> 00:13:59,570
I didn't want to stop you talking.

134
00:13:59,570 --> 00:14:01,730
I think I'll go for four minutes.

135
00:14:01,730 --> 00:14:02,290
Okay.

136
00:14:03,170 --> 00:14:04,110
Oh.

137
00:14:04,110 --> 00:14:04,770
Do you want another minute?

138
00:14:05,350 --> 00:14:05,710
No, no, no.

139
00:14:05,710 --> 00:14:07,170
It's okay.

140
00:14:07,170 --> 00:14:09,550
I normally go over time at this time.

141
00:14:11,090 --> 00:14:13,150
Elena, I was watching the TV.

142
00:14:13,150 --> 00:14:21,030
I was watching the election and I saw someone's face pop up and I went, I know this person and she's running informal politics.

143
00:14:21,030 --> 00:14:24,410
And I went, oh my goodness, it's amazing.

144
00:14:24,410 --> 00:14:26,370
So many facets to you.

145
00:14:26,390 --> 00:14:29,610
And yeah, I'm sure you've got a story to tell.

146
00:14:29,610 --> 00:14:31,850
How did you end up there and doing what you do?

147
00:14:34,610 --> 00:14:35,350
Oh, I don't know.

148
00:14:35,350 --> 00:14:37,770
I mean, how do I end up anywhere?

149
00:14:37,770 --> 00:14:51,750
A combination of kind of accident and also sort of just relentless stubbornness that means I continue to pursue things even though the odds are very much against me, I guess.

150
00:14:52,350 --> 00:15:01,470
And Footscray, I guess, is another classic example of that, where we really, I was running for the Greens, we really had no shot in a safe labor seat.

151
00:15:01,470 --> 00:15:17,430
But we, at the last minute, we got the liberal preferences and it just kind of changed the game and suddenly I was on TV and getting a lot more of Footscray in the coverage than we ever anticipated.

152
00:15:17,430 --> 00:15:24,930
And prior to that, my background is in architecture, but I've always been passionate about environmental sustainability.

153
00:15:25,730 --> 00:15:42,950
And then, through my career, I've become more and more interested in social sustainability and social collaboration as a real means of achieving environmental sustainability and environmental justice.

154
00:15:42,950 --> 00:16:08,810
And Jacques here and one of the stories that he told when I spoke on a panel here previously is actually one that I've used quite recently, and it was around, I think, your children and your daughter suddenly being able to tie her shoelaces and a huge amount of celebration about that happening.

155
00:16:08,810 --> 00:16:22,750
But your reflection, I think, that there had been many weeks and months and years of your son helping her to tie her shoes, and that that had gone by with not much of a remark.

156
00:16:22,750 --> 00:16:36,650
And so I'm very passionate about what it is that we can do together, and not necessarily just the idea that we need to be able to do everything apart and as individuals.

157
00:16:36,650 --> 00:16:40,710
And that is similar to my experience through architecture.

158
00:16:40,710 --> 00:16:53,750
I was working in housing, and I was seeing what we were doing at a high res, kind of high density, and also at urban sprawl and en masse.

159
00:16:53,750 --> 00:16:56,330
And it just wasn't working.

160
00:16:56,330 --> 00:16:57,770
It wasn't working socially.

161
00:16:57,770 --> 00:17:00,830
It wasn't working from an environmental perspective.

162
00:17:00,830 --> 00:17:03,390
And it was all highly individualized.

163
00:17:03,390 --> 00:17:16,650
And as an architect, you either work in that space or you work for individual clients, but there was never an opportunity to kind of capture that collective potential, I suppose.

164
00:17:16,650 --> 00:17:23,089
And so that led me to become interested in Co-Housing and collaborative approaches to housing.

165
00:17:23,089 --> 00:17:32,570
And that's been my real focus for a long time about people being able to come together and co-design where and how they want to live.

166
00:17:32,570 --> 00:17:36,150
And I think that that how bit is really important.

167
00:17:36,150 --> 00:17:44,830
And also to be able to collaboratively govern those spaces and to decide together what it is that they want to achieve.

168
00:17:44,830 --> 00:17:55,190
And not to always having to be battling, I guess, against the system that requires them to do everything on their own.

169
00:17:55,190 --> 00:18:02,470
And I think at some point, around your 18th birthday, you're suddenly told that you don't need to share your toys anymore.

170
00:18:02,470 --> 00:18:07,770
That actually you should go out and get your own car and your own house and all of those sorts of things.

171
00:18:08,990 --> 00:18:12,270
And everything becomes a competition.

172
00:18:12,290 --> 00:18:14,850
And I don't think it has to be that way.

173
00:18:14,850 --> 00:18:19,330
So I'm really interested in how housing can help shift that narrative.

174
00:18:27,140 --> 00:18:29,040
Thank you.

175
00:18:29,040 --> 00:18:31,960
I'm worried that it's gonna pull everything down.

176
00:18:33,140 --> 00:18:34,360
That's me being the fatalist.

177
00:18:41,900 --> 00:18:43,580
Hi, I'm Bridgette.

178
00:18:45,440 --> 00:18:53,360
I get out of bed in the morning in order to hope that we have hope for generations to come.

179
00:18:53,360 --> 00:18:56,260
That's the reason I do what I do.

180
00:18:56,260 --> 00:19:04,520
I don't have children, but I'm surrounded by kids, and I worry a lot about what their world is gonna be like in 30 years.

181
00:19:04,520 --> 00:19:11,560
I think it's about as good as it's gonna get for them right now, which is unfortunate, so just a bit of dystopian in me.

182
00:19:13,340 --> 00:19:32,490
I came to this position after working in design and brand strategy for probably long enough to find my way to a foresight course, and I was fed up, basically, with working on things that lasted 60 seconds, or maybe six months in the market, and that there's gotta be something different.

183
00:19:32,490 --> 00:19:36,470
And I, yeah, found my way to a foresight degree.

184
00:19:36,470 --> 00:19:37,960
So yeah, this is a good place to be.

185
00:19:38,080 --> 00:19:39,800
This is a good space to be in.

186
00:19:39,800 --> 00:19:46,680
And then I had, I think, the good fortune, or a little bit of erratic kind of planning serendipity.

187
00:19:46,680 --> 00:19:49,420
Like, oh, good, this feels right.

188
00:19:49,420 --> 00:19:55,900
I now torment mostly MBA students at Swinburne University who are doing postgraduate studies.

189
00:19:55,900 --> 00:20:02,490
I used to torment design students, and the business will say, can you come do a bit more of that for us over here?

190
00:20:02,490 --> 00:20:03,600
So that's what I do.

191
00:20:03,600 --> 00:20:11,540
And it's great because I just get to ask questions and don't necessarily have answers because we don't always have to have the answers.

192
00:20:11,540 --> 00:20:20,400
And I think that's the thing that I grapple with all the time, that we live within this perception that we need certainty, which is absolute nonsense.

193
00:20:20,400 --> 00:20:24,780
We can't have certainty in a complex adaptive system, end of story.

194
00:20:24,780 --> 00:20:30,100
And yet we constantly pursue this sense of certainty.

195
00:20:30,100 --> 00:20:31,470
And I'm not saying that that's bad.

196
00:20:31,580 --> 00:20:40,040
I'm simply saying that it leaves us with a lack of awareness of all those opportunities that are out there.

197
00:20:40,040 --> 00:20:51,160
And so my interest in what I refer to, and I'm not the only one, as post-growth innovation, is what can we do when what we're doing just has to stop?

198
00:20:51,160 --> 00:20:59,490
And my love is tormenting those students and getting them to ask better questions.

199
00:20:59,490 --> 00:21:02,020
That's really my job.

200
00:21:02,020 --> 00:21:11,970
And I've just come off day two of running a three-day innovation lab with 260 year seven and eight students, which has been amazing.

201
00:21:11,970 --> 00:21:13,440
Yeah, it's really cool.

202
00:21:13,440 --> 00:21:16,520
And we started with futures literacy, so tick.

203
00:21:16,520 --> 00:21:34,460
But that is where I think, that's what gets me out of bed in the morning, knowing that not me making a difference, but helping people ask better questions might help shape a better world in 150 years.

204
00:21:35,900 --> 00:21:37,260
Yeah.

205
00:21:37,260 --> 00:21:37,940
Yeah.

206
00:21:37,940 --> 00:21:39,340
Not the immediate future.

207
00:21:39,340 --> 00:21:40,380
No.

208
00:21:40,380 --> 00:21:43,120
You've written that one off.

209
00:21:43,200 --> 00:21:43,820
Sorry, guys.

210
00:21:48,860 --> 00:21:52,120
Different futurists will give you different takes.

211
00:21:53,820 --> 00:21:55,340
When do you want your positivity?

212
00:21:55,340 --> 00:21:58,720
When do you want your pessimism?

213
00:21:58,720 --> 00:21:59,780
Like a sliding scale.

214
00:22:01,140 --> 00:22:03,160
Okay.

215
00:22:03,160 --> 00:22:07,440
When I was thinking about the question of what drives me, a couple of things came up.

216
00:22:07,440 --> 00:22:12,460
The first is that not a lot drives me because I'm pretty burnt out these days.

217
00:22:14,900 --> 00:22:22,040
Two years of a pandemic, kids in the house locked up and feeling overworked.

218
00:22:22,040 --> 00:22:23,000
I've been getting a lot of rest.

219
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:28,080
I've been doing a lot of yoga, Nidra, which is a sleep meditation.

220
00:22:28,980 --> 00:22:33,760
My experience is it's a practice that enlivens.

221
00:22:33,760 --> 00:22:35,640
It's like, what can drive me?

222
00:22:35,640 --> 00:22:37,140
Well, a sense of rest.

223
00:22:38,980 --> 00:22:51,360
So, you know, I think, and then I think, okay, when I go back to, you know, where I came from, I think there's this kind of, you know, if we're lucky, we have good childhoods.

224
00:22:51,360 --> 00:22:53,060
We get shown a lot of love.

225
00:22:53,060 --> 00:22:54,600
I was given a lot of love.

226
00:22:54,600 --> 00:22:58,140
I was given unconditional love by both my parents.

227
00:22:59,960 --> 00:23:01,220
And I got a lot of rest, you know.

228
00:23:01,220 --> 00:23:03,200
I wasn't, you know, they didn't put me to work right away.

229
00:23:03,440 --> 00:23:07,620
And, you know, I got to enjoy my childhood.

230
00:23:07,620 --> 00:23:09,860
Unlike them, they had very difficult childhood.

231
00:23:09,860 --> 00:23:12,500
They're abusive, you know, environments.

232
00:23:12,500 --> 00:23:22,860
So I think that that kind of bosom, the bosom of love, the bosom of spaciousness of rest is powerful.

233
00:23:23,780 --> 00:23:31,260
And, you know, I think a lot of my ability to operate in the world comes from, from the love that, you know, my parents and other people have given me.

234
00:23:31,260 --> 00:23:35,060
So I think what drives me, well, that's one answer.

235
00:23:35,060 --> 00:23:40,520
I think for me, the other one is, is I grew up amid a lot of contradictions.

236
00:23:40,520 --> 00:23:46,960
So my dad was a history professor, a Chicano rights activist.

237
00:23:46,960 --> 00:23:52,740
My mom, you know, was a community development practitioner.

238
00:23:52,740 --> 00:24:03,400
And they were part of the civil rights movement in the United States, the Chicano power movement, alongside the, you know, African Americans, blacks, Asians, Jews.

239
00:24:03,400 --> 00:24:12,300
It was really a rainbow coalition of different ethnic groups that fought together for rights in the United States.

240
00:24:12,300 --> 00:24:25,700
And so, you know, I got taught a narrative in my high schools that the United States civilized North America and is bringing democracy to the world.

241
00:24:25,700 --> 00:24:28,100
That was the narrative you got in high school.

242
00:24:28,100 --> 00:24:38,280
And then at home, the narrative I got was that the United States committed genocide in North America and it's spreading neocolonialism around the world.

243
00:24:38,280 --> 00:24:40,660
Very different narratives.

244
00:24:40,660 --> 00:24:46,380
And so, I grew up with these very quite, quite different narratives of the world.

245
00:24:46,380 --> 00:24:51,140
And when you grow up like that, you ask yourself who's right, you know?

246
00:24:51,140 --> 00:24:52,520
What's going on here?

247
00:24:52,520 --> 00:25:02,980
And I think, you know, the way I describe it is I grew up in the cracks between these different views of the world, and asking these questions, what's going on here?

248
00:25:02,980 --> 00:25:09,720
You know, why was my best friend circle Japanese American, Guatemalan, Hungarian, and Korean?

249
00:25:09,720 --> 00:25:11,300
Somewhere in Los Angeles, why?

250
00:25:11,300 --> 00:25:17,780
You know, so I think that other thing is just that curiosity born of these contradictions.

251
00:25:17,780 --> 00:25:23,180
And I think that the epic times that we live in today are a time of great contradiction.

252
00:25:23,180 --> 00:25:33,520
And I think that's, you know, it's a challenge, but it's also helps us to think about what the world that we're in and how do we what do we do?

253
00:25:40,090 --> 00:25:52,730
I'm passing the baton back, and I'm gonna pass it right back over in a moment, because the first question that I'd like to pose is to you, Jose, and you've already sort of touched on this.

254
00:25:52,730 --> 00:26:00,030
We're in a period of global, political and climate uncertainty.

255
00:26:01,090 --> 00:26:09,010
There are populist solutions being put forward by both the left, the right, and everyone in between.

256
00:26:10,770 --> 00:26:27,510
We're living in a time where they're just competing solutions, competing ideas, and it's very difficult to map out a future that looks maybe more cooperative, more cohesive.

257
00:26:27,510 --> 00:26:45,730
So I'm just wondering, we're sort of moving from a big picture, and we're gonna drill down a little bit through the conversation, but just to start with, you know, what are the alternatives to where we're at at the moment in terms of this polarization?

258
00:26:45,730 --> 00:26:47,390
Are there alternatives?

259
00:26:47,390 --> 00:26:50,430
How can we build a better future together?

260
00:26:57,680 --> 00:27:11,220
Yeah, okay, so I think the starting point of left-right, so I began sort of thinking left-right, that's how kind of conventional politics is framed.

261
00:27:11,220 --> 00:27:17,100
And that, when I thought about it, I thought, okay, there's some truth in there, but it obscures a lot.

262
00:27:17,100 --> 00:27:21,260
So the truth for me is that we have a billionaire problem.

263
00:27:21,260 --> 00:27:23,320
We got way too many billionaires.

264
00:27:23,320 --> 00:27:29,900
That's very, very simple, clear for me, for me, you know, I'm a socialist.

265
00:27:29,920 --> 00:27:34,280
I voted, you know, I wanted Bernie Sanders to win in the United States, right?

266
00:27:34,280 --> 00:27:37,460
So you know where I sit on the spectrum.

267
00:27:37,460 --> 00:27:40,940
But for me, there's a clear billionaire problem.

268
00:27:40,940 --> 00:27:51,060
And then, according to my colleague, Barat Dahia, we also have a billion people in slums problem, right?

269
00:27:51,480 --> 00:28:01,380
So we're living in a time of absolute extreme inequality, and that is generated by a political economy, by a global political economy.

270
00:28:01,380 --> 00:28:03,920
You know, you can call it a number of different things.

271
00:28:05,280 --> 00:28:23,040
So the truth to left and right is that there is a side that is squarely for equity and for greater equivocality, for greater participation.

272
00:28:23,180 --> 00:28:26,240
And I don't think you can argue against that.

273
00:28:26,240 --> 00:28:29,120
And I don't think you could actually say that that problem doesn't exist.

274
00:28:29,120 --> 00:28:33,440
We've seen it grow and grow and grow and grow for decades and decades and decades.

275
00:28:33,440 --> 00:28:47,640
So from that point of view, I think what gets talked about from the left right point of view, at least in economic terms, to me is fairly, it makes sense.

276
00:28:47,640 --> 00:28:53,500
But where the left right break down is on a couple of other lines.

277
00:28:53,500 --> 00:29:03,360
So for example, if you go historically, the labor in Australia were anti-immigration.

278
00:29:08,600 --> 00:29:10,340
What was the policy in Australia?

279
00:29:10,340 --> 00:29:12,420
Yeah, what Australia policy?

280
00:29:12,420 --> 00:29:14,780
Supported by unions.

281
00:29:14,780 --> 00:29:20,400
The unions in the United States also supported anti-immigration in the United States.

282
00:29:20,900 --> 00:29:24,000
So it's thematically, it's a pattern, right?

283
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:25,680
It isn't just anecdotal.

284
00:29:27,800 --> 00:29:29,640
So you have these crossovers.

285
00:29:31,260 --> 00:29:32,540
You have the teal here.

286
00:29:32,540 --> 00:29:35,880
So we're talking, the teal, the recent election, right?

287
00:29:35,880 --> 00:29:51,180
And they're supposed to be liberal kind of suburbs, but now they're worried about climate change and they have LGBTQ kind of affiliations or empathies, okay?

288
00:29:51,180 --> 00:29:52,660
So they're moving in that direction.

289
00:29:52,660 --> 00:29:54,760
So there's some crossovers there.

290
00:29:56,080 --> 00:30:02,080
But for me, it really breaks down when you begin looking at the bigger historical changes.

291
00:30:02,080 --> 00:30:22,860
So when I really started thinking about left, right, one of the interesting things that we've seen over the last several centuries is the two primary choices that we had, socialism, capitalism.

292
00:30:25,320 --> 00:30:27,960
They're both products of the Enlightenment.

293
00:30:29,140 --> 00:30:34,920
And they are both what we might call modernizing ideologies.

294
00:30:35,700 --> 00:30:46,680
They're ideologies that, they're humanist, so they saw humans as imposing, you know, our will on the world.

295
00:30:46,680 --> 00:30:51,400
Rationalist, we can figure things out using our minds, right?

296
00:30:51,780 --> 00:30:54,440
We can apply order to the world.

297
00:30:55,620 --> 00:31:09,440
But when you look at the results of these ideologies, both left and right, in the Soviet Union, in socialist countries, and in the United States, it's absolute disaster over the last several centuries.

298
00:31:09,440 --> 00:31:16,540
And so this is why people like Bov and Duda de Jesus Santos talk about left-right as Western constructs.

299
00:31:16,540 --> 00:31:27,260
Say, they are products of the Enlightenment and Western modernity, and they both alienated fundamentally from the living systems that we're in.

300
00:31:27,280 --> 00:31:31,460
Or, in other terms, they're imperial formations that are extractive.

301
00:31:32,120 --> 00:31:41,580
They're about using the resources and people within whatever periphery as much as possible.

302
00:31:42,760 --> 00:31:46,740
And they do not have a living systems view of the world.

303
00:31:46,740 --> 00:32:12,460
So from that point of view, left-right begins to become much more of a, both a Western construct, it looks much more as a rupture from kind of these pre, these sort of indigenous ways of thinking or ways of thinking that were more connected to the land, or an understanding of how living systems actually work.

304
00:32:12,460 --> 00:32:16,820
So then from that point of view, you can begin saying, well, what comes after, right?

305
00:32:16,820 --> 00:32:21,100
And so for me, what comes after are, I mean, there's a lot of things that are going to come after.

306
00:32:22,240 --> 00:32:31,960
These ways of thinking, thinking that are divorced from our living systems, they can't survive because we won't survive if they survive, right?

307
00:32:31,960 --> 00:32:33,280
So new forms of thinking.

308
00:32:33,280 --> 00:32:41,280
So I've been watching the peripheral, William Gibson story on prime.

309
00:32:42,860 --> 00:32:48,620
And there's a term called, in the future, this is like a futuristic kind of scenario.

310
00:32:50,140 --> 00:32:53,140
The revolutionaries are called neoprims.

311
00:32:53,140 --> 00:32:56,360
Neoprims just stands for neoprimitives, right?

312
00:32:56,360 --> 00:33:01,800
And the neoprimitives are basically saying we have to get, we have to go back to square one, right?

313
00:33:01,800 --> 00:33:03,600
Technology is out of control.

314
00:33:03,600 --> 00:33:06,560
We've completely destroyed ourselves and the world through technology.

315
00:33:06,560 --> 00:33:11,060
So there's this, kind of this radical anti-technological view, right?

316
00:33:11,060 --> 00:33:14,880
So that's, I'm not saying that's not the alternative I want, right?

317
00:33:15,360 --> 00:33:20,600
But that begins to see the rupture out of that left-right modernity.

318
00:33:22,780 --> 00:33:32,140
For me, the core concept that I want to put forward about, you know, sort of future thinking is the commons.

319
00:33:32,140 --> 00:33:40,760
And I see the commons as that which we all mutually depend on for our survival and well-being, right?

320
00:33:40,960 --> 00:33:44,880
What is it that we mutually depend on for our survival and well-being?

321
00:33:45,820 --> 00:33:59,040
And if you look at that concept of what we mutually depend on our survival and well-being, there's a logic that I call implication.

322
00:33:59,040 --> 00:34:05,540
And what that means is that people are implicated into shared concern.

323
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:30,780
So, you know, wind back to early 19th century and unions here, white male unionists are worried about losing their jobs to these foreigners, and they mutually implicate themselves into, well, we have to protect our jobs.

324
00:34:31,880 --> 00:34:37,300
But of course, they've excluded a whole number of other groups at the same time, right?

325
00:34:37,300 --> 00:34:50,139
So this logic of implication can be an exclusivist logic of implication, but it can also be a logic of implication that draws a larger group of people in.

326
00:34:50,139 --> 00:34:54,179
So we know that without a safe climate, we're all stuffed.

327
00:34:54,179 --> 00:34:56,380
We're all just completely stuffed.

328
00:34:56,380 --> 00:35:05,100
And so a safe climate is a commons, it's an atmospheric commons that we all mutually depend on for our survival and well-being.

329
00:35:05,100 --> 00:35:06,520
And that implicates all of us.

330
00:35:06,520 --> 00:35:10,700
And it doesn't matter if you're a white unionist or, you know, someone else.

331
00:35:10,700 --> 00:35:12,320
It doesn't matter.

332
00:35:12,320 --> 00:35:17,500
And so this is when the exclusivist implication begins to break down.

333
00:35:17,500 --> 00:35:23,120
So somewhere in there, I see the future of political ideology.

334
00:35:23,120 --> 00:35:38,140
In the breakdown of the exclusivity, and the opening and the implication into larger forms of thinking about how we're part of commons, how we need to fight for those commons, how we need to mobilize together for those commons.

335
00:35:49,960 --> 00:35:59,640
Yeah, I was just reflecting the other day when, you know, there's this whole thing with woke, you're woke, and it came out of the US, that sort of thing.

336
00:35:59,640 --> 00:36:08,920
And then I was thinking about, I was watching, you know, Trump stuff, and I was talking about the great awakening.

337
00:36:08,920 --> 00:36:22,620
And so one's woke, one's awakening, and they're almost sort of, it's strange that they're saying very sort of, on one level, quite, I've woken up, but they've woken up either way.

338
00:36:22,620 --> 00:36:45,900
And it's still that sort of same kind of thing that's come from the same sort of lineage that you're talking about, rather than talking about something new altogether, which is why we've come together, and why we have Brigitte, who, I'm just sort of thinking you might be able to reflect a little bit on what Jose's been talking about.

339
00:36:46,720 --> 00:36:55,240
And maybe get a little bit more practical about what we can do at the grassroots level.

340
00:37:02,060 --> 00:37:06,880
Moving from the bigger picture to the local level, what we can do.

341
00:37:13,980 --> 00:37:33,300
Oh, so I'll start actually by reflecting on the day, the two days that I've just spent with these students, because what has completely, what's kept me enthralled and also blown me away is their capacity for imagination.

342
00:37:33,300 --> 00:37:42,000
So I've got students who are imagining incredibly powerful and equitable uses of technology.

343
00:37:44,500 --> 00:37:49,340
And ideas for better futures, because that was part of my question.

344
00:37:50,520 --> 00:37:55,820
But there was no one better future shared amongst those 260 students.

345
00:37:57,980 --> 00:38:09,340
So this notion that 260 people can come together, they've been working in groups of four, five, six, depending on how engaged they were or not, is wonderful.

346
00:38:10,860 --> 00:38:20,020
But the first part of yesterday was spent negotiating differences in what they would conceive to be a better future.

347
00:38:20,020 --> 00:38:21,960
So they're all at the same school.

348
00:38:21,960 --> 00:38:33,080
They, I won't say they come from similar walks of life, but they are in a school where there's a set of values and beliefs that are professed by the school and espoused by the students.

349
00:38:33,080 --> 00:38:36,820
And that's great, but there's still no one shared vision.

350
00:38:36,820 --> 00:38:38,420
So it goes to your point about Commons.

351
00:38:39,740 --> 00:38:52,000
That they share their existence within the school, but beyond that, they have attention to gender and gender equity, respectful of difference and diversity.

352
00:38:53,240 --> 00:39:08,920
But when I see that as a community and think you're all in the same school, you're kind of being taught the same stuff, and I'll use the word catechism quite deliberately, that there is a set of beliefs that's being taught, and there is a great deal of difference.

353
00:39:08,920 --> 00:39:19,600
So in terms of local, the things that immediately come to mind are particularly your question about we wanting or wanting a better future.

354
00:39:19,600 --> 00:39:20,980
Who's the we?

355
00:39:22,140 --> 00:39:28,240
What's better, depending on who you are and your positionality and situation in the world, and your situatedness?

356
00:39:29,880 --> 00:39:34,640
And when we talk about local communities, how is that defined?

357
00:39:34,760 --> 00:39:42,200
So reflecting on your school friends, local community, but very diverse backgrounds.

358
00:39:42,200 --> 00:39:49,540
Until I moved to Ballarat, my best mate, well, one of my best mates lived in Ballarat, one in Canberra and one in London.

359
00:39:49,540 --> 00:39:51,940
They were my community.

360
00:39:51,940 --> 00:39:58,560
And I think part of the challenge here is understand what we define as local, what we define as community.

361
00:39:58,560 --> 00:40:03,580
And I'm particularly intrigued about building better social and economic relationships.

362
00:40:04,700 --> 00:40:11,220
Because we tend to bundle social and economic together all the time.

363
00:40:11,220 --> 00:40:19,260
And it seems that economics drives a lot of the capturing of what we define as relationships or how we want to build those relationships.

364
00:40:20,400 --> 00:40:25,680
So to go to your real question, how do we creatively and practically do it?

365
00:40:27,200 --> 00:40:48,300
There's been a lot of attention to, and I'm speaking at this from the perspective of a foresight practitioner who works around innovation, there's been a lot of attention to design-led innovation and practices that are design-centric and human-centric with little regard to anything beyond the human centricity.

366
00:40:48,300 --> 00:40:53,600
Design is complicit in material consumption and not always in a good way.

367
00:40:56,140 --> 00:41:11,340
Because design can do great things, but the way we do stuff, the way we operate, particularly in those community and economic and social structures, is building on exactly what you've just talked about.

368
00:41:11,340 --> 00:41:17,640
So that continuation of the business as usual around the ideologies.

369
00:41:19,040 --> 00:41:21,560
Even left and right, I've just become so tired of the term.

370
00:41:22,460 --> 00:41:25,800
And I've always questioned it, like why is it left and right?

371
00:41:25,800 --> 00:41:26,640
Where did that come from?

372
00:41:26,640 --> 00:41:30,740
Because left in some cultures means something different from other cultures.

373
00:41:30,960 --> 00:41:34,660
Why do we have them as completely polar opposites?

374
00:41:34,660 --> 00:41:44,540
I was working on a project a few months ago, and we did some research which suggested that survey design could be improved in terms of responsiveness.

375
00:41:44,540 --> 00:41:56,420
So not just the survey design itself, but the redesign of a survey so that there was not the automatic placement of multiple-choice answers ranging left to right.

376
00:41:56,420 --> 00:42:17,640
So when you have a scale and you have an options left to right, stop doing that because for someone who reads right to left and has low language capability, even if they're looking at the survey and bother to continue it, they're not necessarily going to respond according to the mechanics that you've used to set up survey because their disposition is to read another way.

377
00:42:18,980 --> 00:42:20,820
Long lists of stuff doesn't work either.

378
00:42:20,820 --> 00:42:22,240
So why am I saying this?

379
00:42:22,240 --> 00:42:26,860
Because we continue to work with systems that propagate the systems that we're in.

380
00:42:26,860 --> 00:42:48,500
And that for me is the challenge around the community, that the practical application within communities, that we talk about practices that are grounded in beliefs and value sets that are not necessarily shared and are complicit in continuing what it is that they have already established.

381
00:42:48,500 --> 00:42:58,340
I've also been doing some work with Victorian Parliament, helping them through a co-design activity so that we can teach them co-design.

382
00:42:58,340 --> 00:43:19,100
And that for me is still a really difficult position because we're kind of imposing, even though we believe that our approach to co-design is based on community practices, has been informed by different cultural approaches, including Indigenous, Australian, including other ethnic practices.

383
00:43:19,100 --> 00:43:21,600
I think that's the term we agreed on using.

384
00:43:23,140 --> 00:43:33,240
But that has been difficult because we're still imposing a system developed by practitioners, and that it feels like there is this kind of recolonization of stuff.

385
00:43:33,240 --> 00:43:47,660
So even when we think about building new communities, is it coming from a deeper foundation and starting again, breaking it down, and starting with something not new for the sake of newness, but different?

386
00:43:47,660 --> 00:43:52,020
Or are we still basing it on foundations that we are surrounded by?

387
00:43:52,020 --> 00:44:00,220
And that's the tension for me, which is why I'm definitely in that dark corner, because my dystopia might be your utopia.

388
00:44:01,320 --> 00:44:05,580
And that is one of the challenges within local communities.

389
00:44:05,580 --> 00:44:26,840
It was just made evident to me today with these students that even when the group of four, passionately working towards that, one of the groups wants to build, wants to convert churches into places where women fleeing domestic violence with their kids can go, because they're connected with the word sanctuary.

390
00:44:29,260 --> 00:44:33,400
And the immediate response within the school was, oh, you couldn't do that with churches.

391
00:44:36,120 --> 00:44:51,880
And the students were really quite taken aback by this, because they felt that their understanding of what a church is and around sanctuary was at odds with what they were being told was, this is what the church does and this is how it operates and you could never do that.

392
00:44:51,880 --> 00:44:52,200
Anyway.

393
00:44:57,840 --> 00:44:59,380
Well, I love that.

394
00:44:59,380 --> 00:45:04,320
Going back to the roots of a sanctuary that was, yeah, it's beautiful.

395
00:45:04,320 --> 00:45:07,080
Yeah, yeah.

396
00:45:07,080 --> 00:45:18,360
Well, we've gone from big picture, little bit more local, and now I'm gonna ask a technologist a really, isn't there an app for that?

397
00:45:19,500 --> 00:45:23,300
You know, there seems to be an app for everything.

398
00:45:23,300 --> 00:45:33,980
So silicon Valley, they'll find, you know, sometimes it's almost like they'll just grab a problem, figure out a solution, and we'll all be better off.

399
00:45:33,980 --> 00:45:39,120
But is that the case, and is there an app for that?

400
00:45:40,400 --> 00:45:42,140
That's a question for me.

401
00:45:43,260 --> 00:45:44,660
Not for me.

402
00:45:47,840 --> 00:46:05,020
Well, different groups have different answers, and unfortunately, the group who started building the whole tech, they think there could be an app for everything, and they can figure it out, and that answer, what they believe, is unfortunately affecting our lives.

403
00:46:05,020 --> 00:46:16,140
One of the things I noticed, I was a programmer, and very soon I realized there's a dynamic, this is how I put it.

404
00:46:16,140 --> 00:46:26,740
Other people may not put it this way, but I realized that programmers are just finding themselves, there's a whole new technology that no one knows how to, it's not regulated.

405
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:41,180
I did electrical engineering, heavily regulated, it's all different level certifications, all hierarchies, but while I was studying electrical engineering, second year, I started my company in IT, and I was getting contracts.

406
00:46:41,180 --> 00:46:59,560
So it was new, and nobody knew about it, and obviously those who have nothing to do, like first, second year students, they explore and they learn very quickly, and in the absence of any certificate, regulation, law, anything, they learn how to do it, and they end up becoming the ones who can't do it.

407
00:46:59,560 --> 00:47:31,600
So this started becoming a problem that later in life, I can articulate what the problem is, which you can see in the startup boom that happened in San francisco, and later we saw in blockchain movement, if you call it a thing, that people who find themselves in a position of a particular ability that others don't have, they think they know better, and others have to listen, unfortunately, to what they think.

408
00:47:31,600 --> 00:47:47,540
So people who could code, they found themselves in a position of coming up with solutions, and imposing those solutions, rolling those things out, and because they were employing computers, they didn't need to consult with anybody, basically.

409
00:47:47,540 --> 00:48:04,980
Rolling out, and I think it, I may be wrong here, like those who know history better, that was followed by the whole globalization movement, and there were already treaties and infrastructure in place for imposing your solutions to a greater scale.

410
00:48:04,980 --> 00:48:16,020
And so all of a sudden, you find people in the, like sometimes teenagers or early 20s, now running companies and coming up with solutions, and everybody is basically listening to them.

411
00:48:18,040 --> 00:48:48,440
And so this is, the main problem is, I'll cut it short now, point I'm trying to make is that just premium laborers, as technology says, or those who can't code have found themselves in a position of doing the solutions, and there is those who have been scholars, or have been academia, or the problem owners, those in the community building, who needs to be in forefront and basically hire these laborers.

412
00:48:48,440 --> 00:49:04,400
Unfortunately, they're those who just have to chase after like the new feature on Twitter, on Facebook, and what we can do now, what we can't do, and so I don't know if I didn't answer your question, I think I just made the whole thing more.

413
00:49:05,840 --> 00:49:15,100
So I can go on about this, but I would like to hear reflections from other people to know how much this resonates with other people, and I can build on that.

414
00:49:16,160 --> 00:49:21,460
I mean, it's as much about asking good questions and laying out the table.

415
00:49:21,460 --> 00:49:24,860
We've literally got a table in the middle there.

416
00:49:24,860 --> 00:49:26,680
And then we're gonna open it up for a discussion.

417
00:49:26,740 --> 00:49:33,860
But there's one last question, Elena, before we open it up to everybody else.

418
00:49:33,860 --> 00:49:36,580
And you mentioned housing.

419
00:49:36,580 --> 00:49:40,460
And we've talked about, you know, the kind of future we want.

420
00:49:40,460 --> 00:49:42,120
And there could be an app for that.

421
00:49:42,120 --> 00:49:48,980
And there's a very famous app, which is Airbnb, which initially started out, you know, fantastic.

422
00:49:48,980 --> 00:49:50,300
Got a spare room.

423
00:49:50,300 --> 00:49:51,540
There's a traveler.

424
00:49:51,540 --> 00:49:53,980
They need a spare place to stay.

425
00:49:53,980 --> 00:49:54,700
Fantastic.

426
00:49:54,800 --> 00:49:57,140
Let's set up a platform.

427
00:49:57,140 --> 00:50:00,100
You know, it's going to be about a sort of a sharing economy.

428
00:50:00,100 --> 00:50:05,180
And but then there was some maybe other consequences down the track.

429
00:50:05,180 --> 00:50:10,140
So I'm just wondering if you have any kind of comments on that.

430
00:50:10,140 --> 00:50:16,200
And yeah, maybe if there are some alternatives out there.

431
00:50:17,840 --> 00:50:20,180
I have many comments about it.

432
00:50:22,460 --> 00:50:37,180
I think part of the whole Airbnb situation is just that it's a demonstration about a lack of sophistication and diversity in the way that we conceive of planning and the economics of housing.

433
00:50:37,180 --> 00:50:56,480
And I think Airbnb kind of the roots came, I think, from a really good place, which was sort of couchsurfing and help ex and kind of this peer to peer kind of exchange, where it was very relational.

434
00:50:56,480 --> 00:51:03,440
You connected directly with the person, you negotiated the terms of use, and all of those sorts of things.

435
00:51:03,440 --> 00:51:19,500
You met with those people and exchanged stories, they got local knowledge, you got stories of their travels, and you exchanged room for some laborer and woofers and all of those sorts of things.

436
00:51:20,520 --> 00:51:27,180
And then somewhere along the line, someone thought, I can extract money out of this.

437
00:51:27,180 --> 00:51:41,080
And so you got this whole sharing economy where these intermediaries don't have to have any assets like Uber and Airbnb.

438
00:51:41,080 --> 00:51:49,420
The people have the assets and the other people have the money that they're going to spend to use them.

439
00:51:49,420 --> 00:51:56,120
And there's a complete breakdown in the personal relationship.

440
00:51:56,120 --> 00:52:00,460
And I feel that that is where the challenge is.

441
00:52:00,460 --> 00:52:06,800
And that's what we have to try and bring back into the idea of the Commons.

442
00:52:07,760 --> 00:52:14,860
And it's kind of similarly the problem with the way that we conceive of governance in general.

443
00:52:14,860 --> 00:52:23,160
It's sort of too big and we need to go down to maybe bioregional governance at that level.

444
00:52:23,160 --> 00:52:28,800
And that's one of the reasons that I'm so interested in Co-Housing and collaborative housing.

445
00:52:28,800 --> 00:52:38,540
Because I feel like it's a good size for people to actually practice working together again.

446
00:52:38,540 --> 00:52:48,340
And we've been conditioned socially to not talk about money, not talk about religion, not talk about politics.

447
00:52:48,340 --> 00:52:51,000
And where does that lead us?

448
00:52:51,000 --> 00:53:03,420
It leads us to people losing their mind on social media, attacking each other rather than being able to have really insightful and sophisticated conversations.

449
00:53:04,620 --> 00:53:08,720
So, my interest is how do we bring that back?

450
00:53:09,340 --> 00:53:13,180
And I think it's kind of coming through in politics as well.

451
00:53:13,180 --> 00:53:20,420
If you don't have the diversity and sophistication between labour and liberal, you get the Greens.

452
00:53:20,420 --> 00:53:25,760
And if you don't have sophistication between Greens and the Liberal Party, you get the Teals.

453
00:53:25,760 --> 00:53:33,420
And if you don't have sophistication and conversation and discussion between the Greens and Labour, you get the Socialists.

454
00:53:33,420 --> 00:53:41,900
So, I think in a lot of places, we are seeing that diversity trying to emerge.

455
00:53:41,900 --> 00:53:45,880
And I think we need to do the same thing in housing.

456
00:53:45,880 --> 00:53:55,040
And we could have people who have an attic or a basement, and they can rent it out long term to people.

457
00:53:55,040 --> 00:53:59,100
But our planning scheme doesn't really allow for that.

458
00:53:59,680 --> 00:54:04,520
Our systems don't allow for co-ownership and other sorts of models.

459
00:54:04,520 --> 00:54:10,660
So, we just have speculation and people accrue it.

460
00:54:11,340 --> 00:54:17,160
And that's just the kind of framework that has been offered.

461
00:54:17,160 --> 00:54:23,900
But it doesn't mean that it has to limit our imagination and what we can do in the future.

462
00:54:26,840 --> 00:54:29,660
The kind of follow-on from Airbnb, I guess.

463
00:54:29,660 --> 00:54:52,900
My fear is that that will lead us into things like co-living and build-to-rent, which will then be owned by huge corporations or even just big super companies whose, you know, their responsibility is to shareholders rather than to the tenants that they might be supporting.

464
00:54:53,160 --> 00:55:09,340
And from a tech and app perspective, they will know when you swipe in and out of your building, when you have visitors, when you order food, when you use the gym or all of these sorts of things.

465
00:55:09,340 --> 00:55:18,040
So there's a whole other level of surveillance that might be coming in the way that we manage these buildings.

466
00:55:18,160 --> 00:55:35,840
And so I think it's really important that we conceive of a shared approach that is collaborative ownership and cooperative ownership, where the tenants are the landlords and it's not a monopoly kind of proposition.

467
00:55:37,680 --> 00:55:39,100
I'll stop there.

468
00:55:40,640 --> 00:55:44,220
Well, we have had a lot of insights from our panel.

469
00:55:44,900 --> 00:55:50,580
And the idea is really to start to imagine different kinds of futures.

470
00:55:50,580 --> 00:55:56,940
So I'm sure that there's a few questions that might be brewing.

471
00:55:56,940 --> 00:56:08,580
Before I open it up, maybe just have a little chat to the person next to you about some of the things that you've listened to and have come up for you.

472
00:56:08,580 --> 00:56:14,700
And then I will go hush again, and then we'll jump in to some questions.

473
00:56:14,700 --> 00:56:25,940
So feel free to just have a chat to the person next to you, and just maybe talk about some of the questions that have come up for you through hearing our panel.

474
00:56:25,940 --> 00:56:33,640
And I'll just do that for about a minute or two, and then we'll have a roving mic, and then we can throw it to the floor with the panel.

475
00:56:33,640 --> 00:56:36,500
So over to you to have a quick chat with the person next to you.

476
00:56:39,760 --> 00:56:42,580
All right, let's bring it back.

477
00:56:45,220 --> 00:56:55,280
So Sonja down the back there has a roving microphone, and we've heard some fascinating things from our panel members, and you've just had a conversation about it.

478
00:56:55,280 --> 00:57:14,800
And one of the great things about these sorts of events is you bring people together who get to meet each other, and you are able to sort of discuss these sorts of issues with people maybe that you've never met before, and that we can derive some really good questions from that.

479
00:57:14,800 --> 00:57:17,500
So it's a good opportunity to have a chat.

480
00:57:17,500 --> 00:57:18,480
Now it's over to you.

481
00:57:18,480 --> 00:57:19,740
Sonja's got the roving mic.

482
00:57:19,740 --> 00:57:22,180
Who would like to ask the first question?

483
00:57:22,180 --> 00:57:27,420
And feel free to direct it to a panel member or just generally.

484
00:57:29,840 --> 00:57:33,480
This is an old drum that I keep banging on.

485
00:57:33,480 --> 00:57:43,180
I wish that something more could be done to make tiny housing acceptable and prevalent.

486
00:57:43,180 --> 00:57:45,900
Everybody wants their own space.

487
00:57:45,900 --> 00:57:49,880
And I agree with what you said about basements and attics.

488
00:57:49,900 --> 00:57:55,920
And the problem there with, I think under the law, it's called tenants in common for ownership.

489
00:57:58,820 --> 00:58:02,880
But tiny houses are a no-brainer.

490
00:58:02,880 --> 00:58:07,020
I mean, even IKEA is selling flat-packed tiny houses.

491
00:58:08,040 --> 00:58:21,300
So I'm wondering if the panel has any thoughts on what can be done to expedite some common sense at local, state and federal level around tiny houses.

492
00:58:21,300 --> 00:58:24,660
Sorry, I've been banging on this drum for about 25 years now.

493
00:58:27,580 --> 00:58:30,420
Yeah, no, and I'm happy to start there.

494
00:58:30,420 --> 00:58:38,920
I think there are a couple of problems with tiny houses and that essentially a tiny house is the same as a car.

495
00:58:38,920 --> 00:58:45,180
It's a depreciating asset and land is the thing that appreciates in value.

496
00:58:45,380 --> 00:58:58,440
And so, even, and tiny houses per square meter are very expensive even though obviously they're much smaller, so on balance, they end up being an affordable housing option.

497
00:58:58,440 --> 00:59:16,500
Because we have such an unsophisticated relationship between housing and land, they still usually leave people in very precarious situations because you're still reliant on some kind of land owner to be a landlord.

498
00:59:16,500 --> 00:59:20,780
And so, there is still that power imbalance.

499
00:59:20,780 --> 00:59:28,840
I feel though that, I mean, my approach is always the collaborative approach and the collective approach.

500
00:59:28,840 --> 01:00:01,320
And I would be more than excited to see tiny houses being able to, and kind of not necessarily tiny houses on wheels, but small houses, micro houses that are accessible and adaptable, but being implemented in a place that is, where people can co-own the land, or there's some kind of tenure model for the land, in a community land trust or something like that.

501
01:00:01,320 --> 01:00:11,720
And then a way that you can own the dwelling, maybe separately or as part of that in a co-operative fashion.

502
01:00:11,720 --> 01:00:23,800
Tiny houses just on their own though, I fear that there are still structural barriers that would lead to greater inequality and precariousness.

503
01:00:36,400 --> 01:00:40,820
We haven't used the word home because we cease to aim at homes.

504
01:00:41,340 --> 01:00:42,800
We don't want homes.

505
01:00:42,800 --> 01:00:44,840
We want investments.

506
01:00:45,300 --> 01:00:52,260
And it's coming down so heavily, and it's seeping under the door and between the walls.

507
01:00:52,260 --> 01:00:54,280
And we just, we don't want homes.

508
01:00:56,620 --> 01:00:58,680
We want investments.

509
01:00:58,680 --> 01:01:05,980
And investments mean a whole different range of aims and moves and results.

510
01:01:08,160 --> 01:01:10,920
No, I mean, I couldn't agree more.

511
01:01:10,920 --> 01:01:13,840
And I think that that is a huge problem.

512
01:01:13,840 --> 01:01:21,260
And it's the, again, it's the unsophisticated way that we've established housing in relationship to the economy.

513
01:01:21,260 --> 01:01:28,540
And no one wants to touch housing because it's the political economy is all structured around it.

514
01:01:28,540 --> 01:01:32,500
And so is capitalism and consumption.

515
01:01:32,500 --> 01:01:43,260
That's where the individual housing narrative emerged to begin with, so that people would get their box and fill it with stuff and they wouldn't talk to anybody else.

516
01:01:44,520 --> 01:01:47,340
So we do have to go back to the notion of home.

517
01:01:47,340 --> 01:01:55,200
And people don't look, think, they think about education and health as still kind of social infrastructure.

518
01:01:55,200 --> 01:01:59,420
But somehow food and housing should be a commodity.

519
01:01:59,420 --> 01:02:03,300
To me, they're even more primal than the other things.

520
01:02:03,300 --> 01:02:10,760
And if you have housing and food, then you can conceive of improved health and improved education.

521
01:02:12,020 --> 01:02:15,300
But that's not what the economy is set about.

522
01:02:17,120 --> 01:02:19,060
I want to add something to that.

523
01:02:21,640 --> 01:02:25,060
If I may, just add something to that.

524
01:02:25,060 --> 01:02:27,060
I'm not talking as an economist.

525
01:02:27,240 --> 01:02:28,880
It is about economy.

526
01:02:29,320 --> 01:02:32,060
I see people who definitely know much better than me.

527
01:02:32,060 --> 01:02:35,980
But I think it's important to bring this up without diving deeper.

528
01:02:36,620 --> 01:02:48,760
When you learn about how money is created and different economies, what is the stable asset that the Reserve and Central Bank can use, Quantitative Easing and everything.

529
01:02:48,760 --> 01:03:06,100
And in Australia, when you can control the supply of buyers for immigration, as an example, then you end up with a situation where that's actually being used as a mean for regulating the economy, and it's not being seen as home.

530
01:03:06,100 --> 01:03:12,600
Whereas, for example, there's no conversation about just nature and parks and everything.

531
01:03:12,600 --> 01:03:20,780
Whereas in some places, you have to actually travel to get to a place where you can see the sky, because it's all polluted.

532
01:03:20,780 --> 01:03:26,240
And that's a privilege, and there's all sort of economy around it, and the price of lands and everything.

533
01:03:27,320 --> 01:03:36,680
In fact, I've heard even like Q is very expensive, because there was a time where there was pollution in Melbourne, and a high area where...

534
01:03:38,140 --> 01:03:59,980
But if we just come to our census and reset everything, if we could, and just understand that the technology and just basic economy allows everybody to have homes, then we can move on and find something else to use to regulate our economy, that doesn't end up with like leaving a lot of people suffering.

535
01:03:59,980 --> 01:04:15,100
And I don't want to talk much longer, but when I see young people, professionals in their 20s, their goal is to buy a house, and basically they go on a mortgage, and they basically use their earnings to pay for the mortgage in the 20s.

536
01:04:15,100 --> 01:04:22,260
Like that's really sad for me to see, where this is how we run the economy, whereas they should invest in themselves and what they're interested in.

537
01:04:22,260 --> 01:04:22,540
Anyhow.

538
01:04:24,620 --> 01:04:26,580
Oh, he knows I live in Q.

539
01:04:29,560 --> 01:04:31,740
It is great, and it is lovely.

540
01:04:33,500 --> 01:04:37,140
I always lose my left credit when I mention that I live in Q.

541
01:04:37,140 --> 01:04:40,020
Let's throw it over to a question.

542
01:04:40,020 --> 01:04:52,040
Probably for Jose and Bridget, but I think at the very start of the discussion, there was a bit of stuff around, I guess, this binary of whatever left, right, capitalist, socialist.

543
01:04:53,120 --> 01:05:02,160
I mean, I think the title of the panel tonight was kind of in and around, like it hints at platform cooperativism and playing with some things.

544
01:05:02,160 --> 01:05:15,640
In terms of the discourse and stuff going on around techno feudalism and this idea that maybe we're already in a post-capitalist period where we're all kind of becoming neo-servs to like the billionaires.

545
01:05:15,640 --> 01:05:37,640
Like I guess in terms of framing that and actually, because I know a lot of people get like an ostrich effect where they want to stick their head in the sand when they think about these things, but it's kind of pretty hard to deny right now that whatever, if so-and-so over there gets a startup going and Jeff Bezos wants to buy it and they go, fuck you, Jeff Bezos, like I don't want to sell you my startup.

546
01:05:37,640 --> 01:05:42,140
He can deploy so much capital and so much resource that he can just crush him.

547
01:05:42,360 --> 01:05:57,340
So in terms of kind of just like getting that message into people's heads, do you think that that's like a constructive thing, like in terms of like, just again, doing away with this binary, like that this even is what we think it is?

548
01:06:03,300 --> 01:06:08,700
Yeah, I mean, I guess that's why, I love all your comments and where you're coming from, by the way.

549
01:06:08,700 --> 01:06:18,500
That's why I had that ambiguity in the beginning, because I do think we have a billionaire problem, and we have a billion people in slums.

550
01:06:18,500 --> 01:06:23,580
And so the extreme inequality we have is real.

551
01:06:24,280 --> 01:06:28,900
And so left traditionally is about the equity.

552
01:06:29,640 --> 01:06:36,220
It's about the people that don't have enough and support for those people.

553
01:06:36,220 --> 01:06:39,860
It's about access to universities, to schools.

554
01:06:40,660 --> 01:06:45,020
If we really want to understand the left better, we actually need to go back in time.

555
01:06:45,020 --> 01:06:46,400
We need to go to the 19th century.

556
01:06:46,400 --> 01:06:49,660
We need to live in the United States during the time of the robber barons.

557
01:06:49,660 --> 01:07:07,720
That will teach us what left is, because then we'll know what a public library means, what a hospital means, what education means, what decent trade union laws mean, associational laws.

558
01:07:07,720 --> 01:07:08,320
To me.

559
01:07:13,460 --> 01:07:17,520
We don't want to throw the baby out with a bath water.

560
01:07:17,520 --> 01:07:35,160
I think that because we're living in a world of oligarchs, we're living in a world of tech oligarchs, extreme tech oligarchs, obnoxious tech oligarchs, and they've captured the medium.

561
01:07:35,160 --> 01:07:38,060
They've captured the medium of the day.

562
01:07:38,060 --> 01:07:40,060
Marx talked about superstructure.

563
01:07:40,640 --> 01:07:43,680
We're in another version of Marx's superstructure.

564
01:07:44,800 --> 01:07:56,060
I'm some brand of whatever neo-Marxist, B-grade Marxist, whatever, you know, but we can see that recursion.

565
01:07:56,060 --> 01:08:09,560
And so, I don't think we can throw the baby out with a bath water and say, left, right is this kind of, at the same time, they are products of Western modernity.

566
01:08:10,620 --> 01:08:11,560
And where is life?

567
01:08:11,560 --> 01:08:13,340
Where is the web of life?

568
01:08:13,340 --> 01:08:20,899
And also, the commons eats away at those categories, because it says we are all implicated in the survival of our planet.

569
01:08:20,899 --> 01:08:23,520
It doesn't matter who the hell you are.

570
01:08:23,520 --> 01:08:33,040
So, it transgresses the idea that somehow you can be rich and get away with the loot.

571
01:08:33,040 --> 01:08:39,240
No, you can't be rich and get away with the loot if the planet is unlivable.

572
01:08:39,240 --> 01:08:41,840
Right?

573
01:08:41,840 --> 01:08:42,779
Yeah, that's right.

574
01:08:42,779 --> 01:08:43,840
Let's get off to Mars.

575
01:08:43,840 --> 01:08:45,040
Yeah, it's madness.

576
01:08:45,040 --> 01:08:46,460
It's complete madness, you know.

577
01:08:47,920 --> 01:08:49,220
So, I love all your comments.

578
01:08:49,220 --> 01:08:51,479
I think they're spot on.

579
01:08:51,479 --> 01:08:54,840
You know, that's why there's, for me, there's like, don't throw the baby out with the bath water.

580
01:08:54,840 --> 01:08:56,479
There's ambiguity there.

581
01:08:56,479 --> 01:09:01,080
And then, let's eat away at the, let's transgress some of those.

582
01:09:01,080 --> 01:09:22,220
And we, and I think the question you asked is the big challenge, is how do we actually form some kind of coherent way of thinking that can bring this new form of this strength towards equity forward in the context of tech oligarchs that control the media?

583
01:09:22,220 --> 01:09:25,720
You know, it's a phenomenal challenge that we have.

584
01:09:25,720 --> 01:09:30,180
Yeah.

585
01:09:30,180 --> 01:09:34,899
I'm gonna speak to this quickly from an education perspective.

586
01:09:34,899 --> 01:09:41,880
Because one of the things I see a lot of within entrepreneurship and innovation is a solution looking for a problem to solve.

587
01:09:43,399 --> 01:09:47,540
In the name of creating something that they can sell.

588
01:09:47,540 --> 01:09:52,460
So about chasing success, chasing fame, chasing reputation.

589
01:09:53,640 --> 01:10:03,620
And that is something that does not exist in every business school in the world, but it's the prevailing position of most business schools.

590
01:10:03,620 --> 01:10:10,840
And it's sad to think that business schools are stuck within that modernist paradigm of what business is and how it works.

591
01:10:12,080 --> 01:10:22,060
And that in trying to introduce what would be considered unconventional ways of approaching business models, and there's nothing wrong with having a business.

592
01:10:22,380 --> 01:10:23,060
That's it.

593
01:10:23,060 --> 01:10:27,160
And I'm saying that in all, there's nothing wrong with having a business.

594
01:10:27,160 --> 01:10:29,700
It's what's the model of operation?

595
01:10:29,700 --> 01:10:32,560
What's the model and infrastructure that underpins that?

596
01:10:32,560 --> 01:10:35,440
Is it that extractive, exploitative model?

597
01:10:35,440 --> 01:10:38,520
And those are terms that actually get taught as part of a model of growth.

598
01:10:39,860 --> 01:11:00,040
There's a particular model that gets taught in a unit that I won't teach anymore unless they have to read the limits to growth before they get to that model of growth and innovation because the model has been disproven by 2020 and 2021, and yet it still prevails as the dominant paradigm and mode of thinking.

599
01:11:00,040 --> 01:11:17,960
So some of this is down to how people, not about the way they're brought up, but how they are introduced to that business context and what business means, what is the role of business in a functioning society, within a commons and a different way of practising life, what does business mean?

600
01:11:17,960 --> 01:11:21,760
And does the word business have to shift along the way, potentially?

601
01:11:21,760 --> 01:11:28,860
Because we are caught, some of the stuff I'm seeing, that I perceive is this shift, we're in a transition state with a lot of stuff.

602
01:11:28,860 --> 01:11:30,560
And that's a messy place to be.

603
01:11:31,340 --> 01:11:42,720
And it's the students coming through high school, so early secondary students at the moment, the ones that I perceive are going to galvanise that change.

604
01:11:42,720 --> 01:11:47,240
But they're hammering, it's kind of the equivalent of the glass ceiling for women.

605
01:11:47,240 --> 01:11:50,280
They're hammering this stuff and they're chipping away on it.

606
01:11:50,280 --> 01:11:52,340
It's concrete, it's not shifting.

607
01:11:52,340 --> 01:11:59,360
And whilst the prevailing system, the prevailing infrastructure they're exposed to, does not model differently, they have nothing else to follow.

608
01:12:00,160 --> 01:12:02,320
So it's not an answer, it's just a comment.

609
01:12:02,320 --> 01:12:04,620
Because I live and breathe this every day.

610
01:12:04,620 --> 01:12:08,600
And I get absolutely fed up with when I ask students, so what do you want to do?

611
01:12:08,600 --> 01:12:11,340
I want to build this thing and I'm going to sell it for $5 million.

612
01:12:11,340 --> 01:12:13,540
Only $5 million, okay.

613
01:12:13,540 --> 01:12:16,500
By the time you finish your degree, you should be chasing $15 million.

614
01:12:16,500 --> 01:12:19,100
Maybe I should, but you didn't get the sarcasm.

615
01:12:21,180 --> 01:12:24,300
But that's what they're expecting.

616
01:12:24,300 --> 01:12:27,500
That's what they're kind of brought up to do within the education system.

617
01:12:27,640 --> 01:12:29,340
And don't get me started on the education system.

618
01:12:34,580 --> 01:12:36,280
Okay, we've got a question.

619
01:12:39,780 --> 01:12:40,860
Thank you very much.

620
01:12:40,860 --> 01:12:47,940
A lot of what you said resonates a lot with some papers I've been reading recently, or radio programs I've been hearing.

621
01:12:47,940 --> 01:12:50,980
And I can tell you about those later, or the names of them, some of you might want to read them.

622
01:12:52,040 --> 01:12:54,100
But they merge into one another.

623
01:12:54,100 --> 01:13:18,320
But whether it's collaborating with other people, or whether it's the polarization between people who strongly disagree, on one radio program, the person making the argument said, the two key things I think we need here is transparency, to be as transparent as possible, and to be as clear as possible in putting our positions as to why we believe what we believe, or why we want to do what we want to do.

624
01:13:18,320 --> 01:13:25,100
Because without those, we don't really understand what's happening, or the power underneath of what's happening.

625
01:13:25,100 --> 01:13:34,100
And if you don't give people as clear an idea as possible, as to why you think what you're proposing, all you can get is complaint, not a critic.

626
01:13:35,340 --> 01:13:55,860
So and when it comes to mine, for example, I heard something on background briefing about how artificial intelligence, the algorithms, are creating type of dystopian, disfigured horror type woman coming up on the internet, who doesn't want to be like it, doesn't know where she's come from, doesn't know who's written the algorithm to make it be the way she is.

627
01:13:57,120 --> 01:14:08,460
That there's just this murkiness and that links very much to who's controlling, you know, your monoliths and monopolies.

628
01:14:08,460 --> 01:14:24,860
So I'm just wondering in terms of either values, being clear on our values, and how we try and put clarity and transparency into the platforms or into the social change we want.

629
01:14:28,820 --> 01:14:29,200
Yeah?

630
01:14:29,200 --> 01:14:31,740
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

631
01:14:31,740 --> 01:14:35,140
I mean, I can just start briefly while they think.

632
01:14:39,280 --> 01:14:46,520
From a housing perspective and from a commons perspective, some of the terms that I've been reading about is the idea of the prosumer.

633
01:14:46,820 --> 01:14:57,500
So, making the user the kind of catalyst and the person who creates the solution and also is the one that then benefits from it.

634
01:14:57,500 --> 01:15:11,380
And from a housing perspective, I think that that's really powerful because at the moment, we're getting dictated to by the speculative housing market, and people are just consumers in that relationship.

635
01:15:11,380 --> 01:15:29,980
The other thing that I feel is a huge opportunity from a co-housing perspective is that people, they come together, even once they've moved in, they come together at least every month to have meetings with everybody.

636
01:15:29,980 --> 01:15:45,620
And they all have to be really clear and transparent about what it is that they value, what it is that they want, how they're going to share their resources and pull their money for spending within their community.

637
01:15:45,620 --> 01:15:53,380
And you're not allowed to sit back and not participate in the decisions.

638
01:15:53,960 --> 01:15:57,180
You have to be an active member.

639
01:15:57,180 --> 01:16:04,760
And so that means that you are involved in the decision and you're involved in the outcome.

640
01:16:04,760 --> 01:16:08,060
You don't get that everyone else doesn't make the decision.

641
01:16:08,060 --> 01:16:15,320
And then when it gets implemented, you get to sit back and go, oh, well, I thought that was a shit idea from the start.

642
01:16:15,320 --> 01:16:17,400
You know, you don't get to do that.

643
01:16:17,400 --> 01:16:22,380
You get to say what you think up front and everyone gets to discuss that.

644
01:16:22,380 --> 01:16:27,340
And together, you come up with the best possible solution.

645
01:16:28,020 --> 01:16:32,680
And no one's allowed to sit back and kind of just be the dissenter.

646
01:16:32,680 --> 01:16:38,680
And I think that that's really powerful because then you reach a more sophisticated answer.

647
01:16:40,660 --> 01:16:46,520
But you're also all then invested in implementing it.

648
01:16:46,520 --> 01:16:50,900
And then together, that implementation can only be stronger.

649
01:16:56,500 --> 01:17:05,040
Gohm is the person you're talking about, the phantom that the AIs create.

650
01:17:05,040 --> 01:17:07,080
If people don't know about this.

651
01:17:07,080 --> 01:17:13,600
So there's some AI system that just generates this.

652
01:17:14,180 --> 01:17:20,620
When you ask it to picture a woman, it comes up with these horrific images.

653
01:17:20,620 --> 01:17:24,840
Dismembered babies, this woman that looks like she's out of a horror film.

654
01:17:26,840 --> 01:17:28,620
And people don't know what to make of it.

655
01:17:28,620 --> 01:17:29,980
Because it's like, what's going on here?

656
01:17:29,980 --> 01:17:31,860
Is the AI evil?

657
01:17:31,860 --> 01:17:34,820
Is there a demon in the AI?

658
01:17:34,820 --> 01:17:38,540
I actually think it's really cool because it's disturbing.

659
01:17:38,540 --> 01:17:40,980
I think we need to be disturbed.

660
01:17:40,980 --> 01:17:43,460
We definitely need to be disturbed about AI.

661
01:17:43,460 --> 01:17:45,660
We need to be disturbed enough to ask questions.

662
01:17:45,660 --> 01:17:50,680
We need enough of those contradictions to begin to go, what the hell is going on here?

663
01:17:50,680 --> 01:18:00,240
And of course, there's a lot of, if you go down the layers of AI, AI reflects the cesspool of human thinking on the internet.

664
01:18:00,240 --> 01:18:09,660
It's going to regurgitate some combination of something between Putin, Trump and the Kardashians.

665
01:18:09,660 --> 01:18:11,240
You know what I mean?

666
01:18:13,580 --> 01:18:15,780
And that's why it's so damn intelligent.

667
01:18:17,280 --> 01:18:25,820
So I actually think, but more to the point, I mean, we, human beings are, we are technological beings.

668
01:18:25,820 --> 01:18:27,060
We are technological beings.

669
01:18:27,060 --> 01:18:30,100
We are, we don't, we don't create technologies.

670
01:18:30,100 --> 01:18:31,280
We don't do technology.

671
01:18:31,280 --> 01:18:33,060
We are technology.

672
01:18:33,060 --> 01:18:37,040
You know, it's, it's hardwired into, into who we are.

673
01:18:37,040 --> 01:18:41,760
And until we fully grasp that, we're not going to be able to take responsibility for our technology.

674
01:18:41,760 --> 01:18:49,480
We keep on cranking out these technologies, you know, nuclear bombs and, you know, ancient orange and this and this and that.

675
01:18:49,600 --> 01:18:53,520
And like oops, no, it's not oops, right?

676
01:18:53,520 --> 01:18:56,860
We've been doing this for a couple hundred thousand years, guys, right?

677
01:18:56,860 --> 01:18:59,900
So let's, let's, we need to learn, like, we need to learn.

678
01:18:59,900 --> 01:19:05,120
This is a big moment, human beings, to learn what it means to be a human being.

679
01:19:05,120 --> 01:19:09,440
And to, and to re, we have to reinvent ourselves fundamentally.

680
01:19:09,440 --> 01:19:13,300
We, we've been pyrotechnical beings for 200,000 years.

681
01:19:13,300 --> 01:19:16,440
Pyrotechnical, for 200,000 years, we've been pyrotechnical.

682
01:19:17,080 --> 01:19:21,840
And now, the age is telling us, hey, guess what?

683
01:19:21,840 --> 01:19:23,580
You're gonna have to reinvent yourself.

684
01:19:23,580 --> 01:19:24,960
You can't do that anymore.

685
01:19:24,960 --> 01:19:25,840
That's remarkable.

686
01:19:32,960 --> 01:19:37,380
Thank you, such a great question, and brings up a lot of enthusiasm.

687
01:19:41,820 --> 01:19:44,060
So I'm suppressing mine.

688
01:19:44,060 --> 01:19:48,360
So I would like to, yeah, detail to everything you said.

689
01:19:48,360 --> 01:19:52,900
I would like to interest you to a term that is not really talked about at all.

690
01:19:52,900 --> 01:19:54,580
You said AI.

691
01:19:54,580 --> 01:19:56,940
The term I wanna bring up is CI.

692
01:19:56,940 --> 01:20:00,000
And I'm very curious if anyone could even guess what it would stand for.

693
01:20:01,120 --> 01:20:03,480
We don't even talk about it.

694
01:20:03,480 --> 01:20:06,280
I'm actually curious, like, you have guesses?

695
01:20:08,240 --> 01:20:08,800
No?

696
01:20:08,800 --> 01:20:10,180
Well, it's not what I have in mind.

697
01:20:10,340 --> 01:20:12,480
It might be a thing.

698
01:20:12,480 --> 01:20:14,580
Community does, I like that.

699
01:20:15,980 --> 01:20:18,100
No?

700
01:20:18,100 --> 01:20:19,720
Collective, I've got one.

701
01:20:19,720 --> 01:20:21,500
Yeah, collective intelligence.

702
01:20:21,500 --> 01:20:23,800
So not a new concept, obviously.

703
01:20:24,840 --> 01:20:29,140
We have countless examples, evolution, bacteria over millions of years.

704
01:20:29,440 --> 01:20:32,440
Everything I say is factually incorrect, probably, but you get the idea.

705
01:20:32,440 --> 01:20:42,800
Learned how to, like, through quorum sensing, they figure out how many of them are there, and then when it's enough, they just come out and take over.

706
01:20:42,800 --> 01:20:50,660
Then we've got wolves learning how to, you know, leverage on each other's perceptions and signal to each other, and then be humans using our noises.

707
01:20:50,680 --> 01:20:53,760
And myths learn to work.

708
01:20:53,760 --> 01:20:55,960
But all these take time.

709
01:20:55,960 --> 01:20:57,060
Now we have technology.

710
01:20:57,220 --> 01:21:01,160
We have internet, which is fascinating to me.

711
01:21:01,160 --> 01:21:03,000
It didn't have to be this way.

712
01:21:03,000 --> 01:21:08,040
We have one layer, one information layer, which we call internet.

713
01:21:08,040 --> 01:21:13,320
It's very, very, very unusual that all of us are connected to one another in one information layer.

714
01:21:13,320 --> 01:21:29,560
And we have a few young people who can use Twitter to actually announce when there's an earthquake in a place, a few seconds before the local authority in that place, by just reading the tweets of people, oh, is it shaking?

715
01:21:29,560 --> 01:21:31,980
So this is how connected we are.

716
01:21:31,980 --> 01:21:35,660
And I'm also an information architect.

717
01:21:35,660 --> 01:21:39,340
I have also Terry from Linux, he's from Victoria and some other people as well.

718
01:21:39,880 --> 01:21:51,080
We can have very, very sophisticated architecture when it comes to service, in the way they talk to each other, IoT, Internet of Things, all that is done.

719
01:21:51,080 --> 01:21:59,340
We can simply enable us humans kind of bounce information amongst each other, and tap into our collective intelligence.

720
01:21:59,340 --> 01:22:05,780
But we're not doing because I think it doesn't translate into share and assets and things like that.

721
01:22:05,780 --> 01:22:09,240
I think that is a problem, but it's 100% feasible.

722
01:22:09,240 --> 01:22:12,740
It's just more than feasible, it's not even funny.

723
01:22:12,740 --> 01:22:14,980
So that's what I wanted to build on.

724
01:22:19,080 --> 01:22:32,580
I was not going to say collective intelligence, but I was going to comment on the AI and the fact that it is that consolidated perspective and some of it is that cesspool that is in our imaginations.

725
01:22:32,580 --> 01:22:46,260
But it's also that it becomes normative and that those images are out there propagated and continually pervade as a particular response within technology or a technology capability.

726
01:22:47,820 --> 01:23:10,460
And that, as humans, we often just want to see that continue and we become arrogant about that use of technology and we don't consider the unintended consequences, which was your point about, we've been there and we've done this and we should have thought it through and we haven't and we keep doing stuff because it's what we know and we think will get it better the next time.

727
01:23:10,460 --> 01:23:27,720
And that's what concerns me, that the world does have people who just don't take notice of history, do not see that we are repeating our behaviorism past and AI is really good at capturing that.

728
01:23:27,720 --> 01:23:29,400
And so I'm same as Jose.

729
01:23:29,400 --> 01:23:32,060
That was absolutely horrific, but it was awesome.

730
01:23:32,060 --> 01:23:33,320
Did we do anything about it?

731
01:23:33,320 --> 01:23:34,520
Or we'll just get it off the internet.

