01:23:34,520 --> 01:23:37,200
Did anyone say, or do we need to invoke that?

733
01:23:37,200 --> 01:23:43,460
scotland's just released a policy document on the use of AI and ethics in AI.

734
01:23:43,460 --> 01:23:45,320
And do we have one in Australia?

735
01:23:52,210 --> 01:24:04,190
Well, I feel like we've just gotten into it, but it's close to closing time, and it's been fascinating.

736
01:24:04,190 --> 01:24:15,310
And the image that will stick with me is a cross between the Kardashians, Putin and Trump, and that's why we've got these horrific AI images around.

737
01:24:16,270 --> 01:24:18,350
Yes, yes.

738
01:24:18,450 --> 01:24:22,710
That will stay with me, so thanks Jose for that.

739
01:24:22,710 --> 01:24:39,690
Look, I'd really like to thank our panel, and as you can sort of smell a little bit, there's some food over there, which is here, and we've got a bar available, and most of our speakers, I don't think, will be running away straight away.

740
01:24:39,690 --> 01:24:47,570
So there's an opportunity to continue the conversation you had earlier, also with our speakers over a drink and some food.

741
01:24:47,570 --> 01:25:03,270
But before we wrap up completely, I'd just like to hand it back over to Basil, the patron of our cooperative, to maybe close with a few brief reflections on a really multifaceted conversation that we've been having.

742
01:25:09,870 --> 01:25:12,450
This one goes to recording.

743
01:25:16,510 --> 01:25:26,710
But I don't know about, no, I just, it's actually been extraordinary inputs, is that what I can use, that people have used?

744
01:25:26,710 --> 01:25:33,930
It's, so for me to give a reflection is extremely difficult, but I'm going to.

745
01:25:37,030 --> 01:25:51,070
I think the issue is, and there's no straight answer for that, going back to my classical thinking, because we're all trained in classics, is what is.

746
01:25:53,050 --> 01:26:02,270
And all the statements that we have, have come from a particular paradigm of understanding.

747
01:26:04,350 --> 01:26:09,110
And the speakers obviously illustrated their expertise in that area.

748
01:26:09,110 --> 01:26:17,690
But really, the two things they were tossing all the time, I felt, were saying is, what is and what ought to be.

749
01:26:18,890 --> 01:26:22,350
All the left and rights are from what is and what ought to be.

750
01:26:22,350 --> 01:26:25,190
And it comes from that Western paradigm.

751
01:26:25,190 --> 01:26:28,310
But we somehow still have to understand the world that we are in.

752
01:26:30,290 --> 01:26:40,350
And one way of understanding that is, I think firstly, we have to understand, and I like the way to say, Jose, we have to understand what is it to be human.

753
01:26:42,690 --> 01:26:46,110
And that's at stake at the moment.

754
01:26:47,250 --> 01:26:55,290
Because that sensibility and sensitivities have been hijacked by all the things that have been said this evening.

755
01:26:57,830 --> 01:27:01,410
The question, then, is, how do we start restoring it?

756
01:27:02,770 --> 01:27:11,430
And for that to happen, I believe we need to extend this conversation and come to, I like the word, we come to a CI.

757
01:27:13,070 --> 01:27:15,270
We have to understand it.

758
01:27:15,270 --> 01:27:37,150
I learned that when I was in a previous life working with indigenous people, and I used to go every year to the Pitinjaric country and meet the elders, because they used to send a whole cohort down, that's like I was in Adelaide, and their role was, we were trying, saying how do they actually deal with government.

759
01:27:37,150 --> 01:27:43,370
And there was this old elder there who cold-shouldered me.

760
01:27:43,370 --> 01:27:45,490
I was there almost every year for five years.

761
01:27:46,710 --> 01:27:52,330
And I thought I had broken some protocols of courtesy with him.

762
01:27:53,490 --> 01:28:03,850
And then in my fifth visit, he called out, and he said, Basil, which actually is a way to pronounce my name, not Basil, I get Basil, but I don't mind.

763
01:28:03,850 --> 01:28:08,050
I say my acquaintances call me Basil, my friends call me Basil.

764
01:28:08,050 --> 01:28:15,710
Anyway, he said Basil, and I went up to him a bit thinking to get a real admonition.

765
01:28:17,730 --> 01:28:21,910
And what he actually said was, has affected me deeply.

766
01:28:21,910 --> 01:28:27,790
And what he said to me was, just remember this, you're ready to hear this now.

767
01:28:27,790 --> 01:28:35,350
Just remember, we all are connected to one another and connected to everything.

768
01:28:36,930 --> 01:28:41,670
To the mountains, to the trees, to the rivers, and particularly we are connected to every human being.

769
01:28:42,810 --> 01:28:48,050
Yes, we are human, but we have to practice to become human.

770
01:28:49,330 --> 01:28:56,450
And we can only practice to become human if we know how we are going to connect.

771
01:28:56,450 --> 01:28:59,410
And in that connectedness, we will learn.

772
01:28:59,410 --> 01:29:01,970
We will make mistakes, but we will learn.

773
01:29:01,970 --> 01:29:07,630
And that's what I liked about getting the CI, that we have to own what we do.

774
01:29:09,930 --> 01:29:11,490
It's easy to blame.

775
01:29:13,430 --> 01:29:17,530
And say that if we have stuffed it up, we have stuffed it up.

776
01:29:17,530 --> 01:29:22,010
But at least have the courage, what I call a collective courage.

777
01:29:22,010 --> 01:29:24,450
And we start here with ourselves.

778
01:29:24,450 --> 01:29:34,270
And just another reflection, I always believe that the great issues of our time have always been articulated as individual attributions.

779
01:29:36,710 --> 01:29:40,130
For example, the work that I did for years and years was on poverty.

780
01:29:40,130 --> 01:29:44,430
There was a tendency to say people are poor because of their individual attribution.

781
01:29:44,430 --> 01:29:49,070
So in Australian terms, they are a bludger or a slacker or not the full quid.

782
01:29:49,070 --> 01:29:53,210
And if you're from the country, you've got a few loose kangaroos in the top paddock.

783
01:29:54,230 --> 01:30:00,530
But in actual fact, we know that poverty is actually to do with the systemic and structural nature of our society.

784
01:30:01,830 --> 01:30:06,550
We know that racism is also that.

785
01:30:06,550 --> 01:30:11,190
We also know that the gender, sexism, is also that.

786
01:30:11,190 --> 01:30:16,670
And the question then is how do we start progressing?

787
01:30:16,670 --> 01:30:27,610
And we can only progress when we listen to one another and start thinking, yes, the truth then lies between us.

788
01:30:29,450 --> 01:30:37,170
And let us unravel it together and come to a conclusion to act.

789
01:30:39,130 --> 01:30:41,870
And then let us act together.

790
01:30:41,870 --> 01:30:48,990
And that's why I think collaboration, cooperatives, quintessentially means that.

791
01:30:50,210 --> 01:31:08,750
And once we have grasped that, I think, to quote Bolton in his famous play, you know, we can clamour like champions if we have the spit for it.

792
01:31:10,010 --> 01:31:15,650
So my friends and the wonderful presenters, thank you so much.

793
01:31:15,650 --> 01:31:22,210
And Antony and Sonja and everyone here that have come, and particularly the friends that I know, thank you for coming.

794
01:31:29,650 --> 01:31:33,010
And then I'll hand it back to our esteemed Antony.

795
01:31:33,010 --> 01:31:34,150
Thank you.

796
01:31:34,150 --> 01:31:38,310
Well, that was a beautiful way of concluding this evening.

797
01:31:38,310 --> 01:31:52,430
Before we finish up completely, I would just like to mention that we'll send you some information out about a really fantastic opportunity that our cooperative has created with RMIT Forward.

798
01:31:52,430 --> 01:32:00,070
So I mentioned at the start of the conversation, we've got a cooperative co-working space, so a shared space in the middle of the city.

799
01:32:00,070 --> 01:32:05,430
We come together, we corporate members here, so we can run events here.

800
01:32:05,430 --> 01:32:08,430
There's a space in the city and there's a couple of bursaries available.

801
01:32:08,430 --> 01:32:14,710
So free of charge co-working in the middle of the city for the whole of next year.

802
01:32:14,710 --> 01:32:18,690
The focus areas are for these bursaries.

803
01:32:18,690 --> 01:32:25,850
People in midlife looking to change career direction, so that might be you or it might be something that you would like to explore.

804
01:32:26,670 --> 01:32:31,870
And we're also looking at the future of social care, the way we care for each other in communities.

805
01:32:31,870 --> 01:32:37,430
So it's broader than just health or aged care or veteran care.

806
01:32:37,430 --> 01:32:45,650
It's really about exploring how we want to work together in new ways, through the co-operative model and other ways.

807
01:32:45,650 --> 01:32:50,490
But the other part of it is you just get a great little office space, self-directed learning.

808
01:32:50,490 --> 01:33:02,130
You can go any which way you'd like with that topic, explore it, explore with friends at RMIT and other members of the co-operative to build a better future.

809
01:33:02,130 --> 01:33:09,130
We've heard from some great futurists this evening, and we've also had the challenge to act.

810
01:33:09,130 --> 01:33:19,610
So check out those bursaries, and I'd like to again thank our speakers and our patron, and we can finish the discussion together.
